Keep this file always under 60 lines. Document principles here; versions, flags, and command examples belong in each component’s `config.yml`, `*_setup.sh`, `./setup_envs.sh --help`, or README.

## Layout

Five stacks at repo root: `simulation`, `ros2_stack`, `meshroom`, `gauss_splat`, `vla_x3plus`. Each has `config.yml`, a component `*_setup.sh` (e.g. `simulation/simulation_setup.sh`), and `src/`. `ros2_stack` also has a colcon workspace under `ws/`. Large binaries, inputs, outputs, and cloned third-party trees are usually gitignored next to that component.

## Provisioning

Initial install is `./setup_envs.sh` from the repo root: it runs `common_setup.sh` and delegates to each stack’s setup script. Which components run by default vs. `--all` / explicit names is defined in `setup_envs.sh` (see its usage text).

## Dependencies

- Conda stacks (`simulation`, `gauss_splat`, `vla_x3plus`): add Python/pip/conda deps to that folder’s `environment.yml`.
- Native stacks (`ros2_stack`, `meshroom`): add system or distro packages via `common_setup.sh` or the component `*_setup.sh`.
- Do not assume one Python environment for the whole repo; `activate_env.sh` and the ROS setup scripts isolate conda vs system toolchains.

## Private Git access

For private clones, use credentials from `.env` (e.g. `GH_TOKEN` embedded in an HTTPS URL). Public deps use normal `git clone` URLs in setup scripts unless you substitute auth.

## How to run

`source activate_env.sh <component>` from the repo root, then run entrypoints from that component’s directory. Activation is stack-specific: conda env, `/opt/ros/...` + `ws/install` for `ros2_stack`, or Meshroom on `PATH` for `meshroom`—see `activate_env.sh` for the source of truth.

## Cross-component integration

When one stack drives another, prefer subprocess so each process keeps its own environment. Shared artifacts and paths are defined in the relevant `config.yml` and code, not here.
